result.execSummary:
The defendant Paris Lavalle Nunn was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Paris Lavalle Nunn is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Paris Lavalle Nunn was found guilty of OWI (3rd), an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant. 
AS TO COUNT 1:
Court ordered defendant to serve 7 months in the House of Correction, with release to the day reporting center consecutive to any other sentence with credit for 14 days time served. Court ordered defendant to pay a fine of $2400 plus all mandatory costs, penalties, surcharges, and $50.00 ignition interlock surcharge, cash bail to apply, due date of 11/10/16 or an immediate entry of a civil judgment is ordered by the court. Defendant ordered to provide a DNA sample and pay all associated costs.  Court ordered AODA assessment and Driver's Safety Plan.  Defendant to cooperate with any treatment recommended.  Court ordered defendant's driving privileges revoked for a period of 24 months. Court orders defendant restricted to operation of vehicles equipped with an ignition interlock device for 24 months to commence upon eligibility to reinstate license.  Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief, Sentencing Referral Form and Pretrial Incarceration Credit received and filed.

Defendant Paris Lavalle Nunn in court with attorney Kevin Brian Dunn.  Alex T. Mueller appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
AS TO COUNT 1:
Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found the defendant guilty. Judgment of conviction entered.
AS TO COUNT 2:
On motion of the State, Court ordered count dismissed.
WCS Intoxicated Driver Intervention program report, received and filed.
